\section{Perturbations: Psychedelics \& AD}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%



%%%%%%%%%%
\begin{frame}{The Comparator on Psychedelics}
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Simulated a psychedelic state by increasing excitatory gain onto deep pyramidal cells (P1), mimicking 5-HT$_{2A}$ agonist effects (increased cortical excitability)\cite{gendraRestoringOscillatoryDynamics2024}.
    \item Result: deep-layer $\alpha$ power was markedly reduced, and superficial $\gamma$ power was elevated (disinhibition of fast activity).
    \item Even with a matching prediction, the error signal remained abnormally high – the model failed to attenuate prediction errors under this hyper-excitable condition.
    \item Interpretation: Weakened top-down constraints (reduced precision of priors) lead to unfiltered bottom-up signals and excessive prediction errors. This aligns with the REBUS model of psychedelics (relaxed priors $\to$ an “anarchic” increase in error signals).
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}
