\begin{frame}{Perturbation: PV Interneuron Dysfunction (AD Model)}
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Simulated Alzheimer’s-related inhibitory deficit by reducing the strength of PV interneuron ($\mathrm{PV}\to \mathrm{P2}$) synapses (disinhibition of P2)\cite{sanchez-todoFastInterneuronDysfunction2025}.
    \item \textbf{Moderate PV loss (early stage):} gamma power increases and prediction error signals are amplified (hyper-excitable cortex with excessive surprise signals).
    \item \textbf{Severe PV loss (late stage):} gamma oscillations collapse into slow-wave dominance (hypoactive cortex), and error signals are greatly attenuated or absent.
    \item Interpretation: Early interneuron dysfunction causes exaggerated prediction errors (overestimating surprise), whereas advanced dysfunction leads to a breakdown of error signaling (failure to propagate errors).
  \end{itemize}
\end{frame}
